you said I'm not allowed
to wear when we're arguing

55
00:02:18,822 --> 00:02:20,484
'cause it makes you
forget what your point was.

56
00:02:20,508 --> 00:02:22,757
I can't believe I missed it.

57
00:02:22,843 --> 00:02:24,323
I can throw it on again tonight.

58
00:02:25,995 --> 00:02:28,279
I mean, why is he still out?

59
00:02:28,349 --> 00:02:31,783
You said that he would wake up
when you reversed his hypothermia.

60
00:02:31,852 --> 00:02:33,117
Yeah, I said he might.

61
00:02:33,186 --> 00:02:36,120
Or he might eight hours
later or eight days later.

62
00:02:36,189 --> 00:02:38,701
If it's any more than that, we
have a problem, but not until then.

63
00:02:38,725 --> 00:02:41,626
You talk to Russell about it?

64
00:02:41,695 --> 00:02:43,362
He knows about
the eight days thing.

65
00:02:45,715 --> 00:02:47,526
Maybe you should
just check in with him.

66
00:02:47,550 --> 00:02:49,262
You said yourself that he's not

67
00:02:49,286 --> 00:02:50,981
supervising you
that much lately.

68
00:02:51,005 --> 00:02:52,637
There's no news.

69
00:02:52,706 --> 00:02:54,901
If I go to him with this information,
he'll think I've lost my mind.

70
00:02:54,925 --> 00:02:57,365
Well, then he can
come talk to me.

71
00:03:02,633 --> 00:03:04,661
Your hair looks
really nice today.

72
00:03:04,685 --> 00:03:05,918
My hair looks nice every day.

73
00:03:05,970 --> 00:03:08,536
I'm on Bailey's... No.

74
00:03:08,605 --> 00:03:11,601
Last time I was with her, I
ordered the wrong test, twice.

75
00:03:11,625 --> 00:03:13,403
If she has a three-strike
policy, I'm out.

76
00:03:13,427 --> 00:03:14,737
I'm on Jackson's service today.

77
00:03:14,761 --> 00:03:16,456
So even if I cared,
I wouldn't trade.

78
00:03:16,480 --> 00:03:17,813
What is this?

79
00:03:20,033 --> 00:03:21,332
I don't know what that is.

80
00:03:21,402 --> 00:03:24,719
It is a crumb, and it
was stuck to my laptop

81
00:03:24,788 --> 00:03:28,222
after you used it to update my
notes right next to a splotch of

82
00:03:28,292 --> 00:03:31,610
what could either be
pizza sauce or blood.

83
00:03:31,662 --> 00:03:33,061
I think it's pizza.

84
00:03:33,130 --> 00:03:35,075
I was hoping it was
blood, and you were dying

85
00:03:35,099 --> 00:03:38,166
and not just getting pizza
all over my computer.

86
00:03:38,252 --> 00:03:39,813
I'm so sorry. I was
doing my notes late,

87
00:03:39,837 --> 00:03:41,147
and I hadn't eaten...

88
00:03:41,171 --> 00:03:42,204
I'll go clean it off.

89
00:03:43,540 --> 00:03:44,839
These interns are sloppy.

90
00:03:44,908 --> 00:03:46,753
You people are
training sloppy interns.

91
00:03:46,777 --> 00:03:47,987
And I trained you,

92
00:03:48,011 --> 00:03:50,451
which means you're bringing
shame to the whole family.

93
00:03:50,880 --> 00:03:52,180
I just got here.

94
00:03:53,032 --> 00:03:54,699
Swag bags for the Syrians.

95
00:03:54,768 --> 00:03:58,836
Some, um, sweatshirts
and baseball caps, Post-its.

96
00:03:58,906 --> 00:04:00,383
Really cool penlights.

97
00:04:00,407 --> 00:04:01,639
Ooh, those are nice.

98
00:04:01,708 --> 00:04:03,136
You're sending
Post-its to Syria?

99
00:04:03,160 --> 00:04:05,305
Yeah, I'm working with
Doctors Aid International.

100
00:04:05,329 --> 00:04:06,739
We've flown in
two Syrian doctors.

101
00:04:06,763 --> 00:04:08,883
They're general practitioners,
but now with the war,

102
00:04:08,932 --> 00:04:11,866
they've been recruited
to staff the field hospitals.

103
00:04:11,935 --> 00:04:13,480
They're getting
advanced trauma training

104
00:04:13,504 --> 00:04:15,432
with Seattle Pres,
and they're here

105
00:04:15,456 --> 00:04:17,856
for a crash course
in basic surgical skills.

106
00:04:17,925 --> 00:04:20,425
They need to learn what
they can do quick and dirty.

107
00:04:20,494 --> 00:04:22,010
They rope you in?

108
00:04:22,078 --> 00:04:24,646
Mmm-hmm. Which must mean that...

109
00:04:24,715 --> 00:04:27,215
Yeah. Yeah, they're
losing a lot of kids.

110
00:04:29,936 --> 00:04:32,737
Godspeed.

111
00:04:32,806 --> 00:04:34,317
All right, let's get this stuff

112
00:04:34,341 --> 00:04:36,002
with the boxes of supplies
we're sending back with them.

113
00:04:36,026 --> 00:04:37,537
So Bailey got her
genome thing funded.

114
00:04:37,561 --> 00:04:38,801
You got this thing funded.

115
00:04:38,862 --> 00:04:40,607
I need to get my
cartilage project bankrolled

116
00:04:40,631 --> 00:04:41,791
while we still got bank.

117
00:04:44,284 --> 00:04:45,645
Dr. Hunt? Hmm?

118
00:04:45,669 --> 00:04:47,497
Dr. Avery's recommendation
on your burn patient.

119
00:04:47,521 --> 00:04:48,721
Oh. Oh.

120
00:04:48,789 --> 00:04:51,373
Hey. Have you rounded
on Matthew Taylor yet?

121
00:04:51,441 --> 00:04:53,086
He was one of Avery's
patients yesterday.

122
00:04:53,110 --> 00:04:54,471
He was here overnight
for observation.

123
00:04:54,495 --> 00:04:55,672
They were worried
about a concussion.

124
00:04:55,696 --> 00:04:57,073
He'll probably
leave this afternoon.

125
00:04:57,097 --> 00:04:58,140
I think his mom's
coming to get him.

126
00:04:58,164 --> 00:04:59,192
Tell Avery that is fine.

127
00:04:59,216 --> 00:05:01,082
Ready? Yeah.

128
00:05:01,168 --> 00:05:02,267
Um, wait.

129
00:05:02,335 --> 00:05:04,352
His mom is coming
to pick him up?

130
00:05:04,421 --> 00:05:05,987
What, can he walk?

131
00:05:06,056 --> 00:05:07,372
You'll have to ask Dr. Avery.

132
00:05:10,227 --> 00:05:11,526
Joyce Basche.

133
00:05:11,595 --> 00:05:14,212
You and I put in a dialysis
graft two weeks ago.

134
00:05:14,264 --> 00:05:17,210
She's had fevers to 102
and the site is red and tender.

135
00:05:17,234 --> 00:05:19,100
It looks infected.

136
00:05:19,186 --> 00:05:22,554
Maybe you dropped a
pizza crust on her wound.

137
00:05:22,623 --> 00:05:24,523
I told him it's normal, right?

138
00:05:24,575 --> 00:05:26,007
It's red and swollen.

139
00:05:26,076 --> 00:05:29,060
She said come in if
it was swollen or red.

140
00:05:29,113 --> 00:05:31,363
He loves doctors,
you in particular.

141
00:05:31,431 --> 00:05:33,426
You do like spending
time with me.

142
00:05:33,450 --> 00:05:34,894
Get her healthy, we'll
have you over for dinner.

143
00:05:34,918 --> 00:05:36,768
Okay, well, he's right.

144
00:05:36,837 --> 00:05:39,370
So give her a gram of Cefazolin.

145
00:05:39,423 --> 00:05:41,184
It's probably a
post-operative infection.

146
00:05:41,208 --> 00:05:44,792
Dr. Murphy is gonna run some
labs and get an ultrasound.

147
00:05:44,878 --> 00:05:46,239
We'll figure out
what's going on.

148
00:05:46,263 --> 00:05:47,561
Okay.

149
00:05:47,631 --> 00:05:49,981
You tested positive
for the risk factor genes.

150
00:05:50,050 --> 00:05:51,377
It doesn't mean
you're gonna get it.

151
00:05:51,401 --> 00:05:52,667
I know what it means.

152
00:05:52,736 --> 00:05:55,036
It's entirely possible
it means nothing at all.

153
00:05:55,105 --> 00:05:56,737
We need an updated will.

154
00:05:56,807 --> 00:05:58,239
I want you to call the lawyer.

155
00:05:58,308 --> 00:05:59,786
Whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa. Slow down.

156
00:05:59,810 --> 00:06:01,871
Even if you get the
disease, it's decades away.

157
00:06:01,895 --> 00:06:04,412
It might not be.

158
00:06:04,481 --> 00:06:07,215
We have a child and
we're having another child.

159
00:06:07,284 --> 00:06:09,951
Look, right now, it says that
Lexie is Zola's legal guardian

160
00:06:10,020 --> 00:06:12,420
if anything happens to
us. That's not going to work.

161
00:06:12,489 --> 00:06:13,822
No, but...

162
00:06:13,907 --> 00:06:15,339
Derek, we were in a plane crash.

163
00:06:15,409 --> 00:06:16,808
We don't need Alzheimer's...

164
00:06:16,877 --> 00:06:18,393
Potential Alzheimer's.

165
00:06:18,462 --> 00:06:20,745
We need an updated will.

166
00:06:20,813 --> 00:06:23,281
Okay. You're right. I
will contact the guy.

167
00:06:23,333 --> 00:06:24,598
Okay.

168
00:06:42,102 --> 00:06:44,313
Okay, we're gonna
try as closely as we can

169
00:06:44,337 --> 00:06:47,349
to replicate your circumstances
in the field hospital.

170
00:06:47,373 --> 00:06:50,887
The most important skills
you need in a wartime situation

171
00:06:50,911 --> 00:06:52,310
is controlling bleeding.

172
00:06:52,378 --> 00:06:54,813
Normally we'd use lasers
and argon beam coagulators,

173
00:06:54,881 --> 00:06:57,148
but as you can see, for now,

174
00:06:57,217 --> 00:06:59,367
we're only using

175
00:06:59,453 --> 00:07:02,454
the contents of this tray.

176
00:07:08,361 --> 00:07:09,561
Is something wrong?

177
00:07:09,630 --> 00:07:13,531
We... Before had
all of these things,

178
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:16,017
but recently the supply
trucks cannot reach us,

179
00:07:16,086 --> 00:07:18,003
and the electricity
is unreliable,

180
00:07:18,071 --> 00:07:20,922
so many of our
instruments we cannot use,

181
00:07:20,990 --> 00:07:24,559
so if you want to replicate
our circumstances,

182
00:07:24,628 --> 00:07:26,928
we may need to
adjust this slightly.

183
00:07:26,997 --> 00:07:29,642
Please. We're here to
make this work for you.

184
00:07:29,666 --> 00:07:31,232
Thank you. Um...

185
00:07:42,913 --> 00:07:44,712
This is more right.

186
00:07:46,049 --> 00:07:47,232
Also...

187
00:07:57,845 --> 00:07:59,277
Now we go.

188
00:08:01,748 --> 00:08:03,788
Mmm.

189
00:08:04,234 --> 00:08:05,567
Dr. Shepherd, hey.

190
00:08:05,636 --> 00:08:06,979
I wanted to follow
up on the patients

191
00:08:07,003 --> 00:08:08,615
we saw yesterday, 'cause I care.

192
00:08:08,639 --> 00:08:10,617
Ross, you should be learning
something else from someone else.

193
00:08:10,641 --> 00:08:11,951
Oh, I am. I'm covering the pit,

194
00:08:11,975 --> 00:08:14,015
which I can do and
manage your post-ops.

195
00:08:14,077 --> 00:08:15,376
Also, I brought you a latte.

196
00:08:15,445 --> 00:08:16,940
It's not your job
to bring my coffee.

197
00:08:16,964 --> 00:08:18,997
Sorry. I'm here. I had
to get a piece of gum.

198
00:08:19,065 --> 00:08:20,231
I had epically bad breath.

199
00:08:20,300 --> 00:08:22,299
I didn't want it to bowl
you over in the OR,

200
00:08:22,369 --> 00:08:23,618
but I'm all set. See?

201
00:08:23,704 --> 00:08:25,170
I didn't need to see it.

202
00:08:25,239 --> 00:08:27,166
Okay. Well, I'm going
to check your post-ops.

203
00:08:27,190 --> 00:08:28,823
Anything you'd
like me to look for?

204
00:08:28,891 --> 00:08:30,391
Ross already did it.

205
00:08:30,460 --> 00:08:31,810
Spectacular.

206
00:08:31,879 --> 00:08:33,178
Anything we should know?

207
00:08:33,247 --> 00:08:35,196
Yeah, Rachel Dawson's awake.

208
00:08:37,017 --> 00:08:38,383
Um...

209
00:08:38,451 --> 00:08:41,019
Tell Hunt she's up.

210
00:08:41,087 --> 00:08:43,527
We're gonna send you back
with a bunch of equipment,

211
00:08:43,557 --> 00:08:46,035
but if supplies aren't reaching
you and there's no electricity,

212
00:08:46,059 --> 00:08:47,654
then we're gonna have
to figure out another way.

213
00:08:47,678 --> 00:08:49,110
Yeah, so take a look around

214
00:08:49,179 --> 00:08:51,879
and see what items you do
have left in the field hospital,

215
00:08:51,948 --> 00:08:53,848
and, uh, put it in the box.

216
00:08:55,769 --> 00:08:56,769
Mmm-hmm.

217
00:08:59,005 --> 00:09:01,072
Dr. Hunt. Can I borrow you?

218
00:09:03,009 --> 00:09:04,943
I don't think I
should go in there.

219
